Figures \ref{fig:LLNL_energy_sankey} and \ref{fig:LLNL_CO2_sankey} and 
Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}
show that households use 15.7\% of U.S.\ energy and are responsible for 19.3\% 
of U.S.\ CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!household} in 2018. 
Therefore, Chapter~\ref{chap:households} considers the sustainability 
challenges of households. 
Likewise, the energy use (37.3\%) and CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!transportation} (36.3\%) of transportation 
motivated Chapter~\ref{chap:transportation}.
This chapter considers agriculture as an import example of industry and commerce
(the other two sectors in Table~\ref{tab:corrected_co2_emissions}).

Agriculture, forestry, and other land use account for an estimated 23\% 
of anthropogenic greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions~\cite{SRCCL2019}. 
Agriculture has strong links to land use, which is the focus of 
Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}.
Chapters~\ref{chap:households} and~\ref{chap:transportation} hint
that land use has strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} implications. 
Those hints become much more concrete and explicit in this chapter and 
in Chapter~\ref{chap:land_use_urban_planning}. 
Agriculture is the major use to which humans put the land.
It is estimated that 71\% of ice-free land is used for agricultural purposes:
12\% for crops, 
37\% for pasture\index{pasture}, and 
22\% for timber production\index{timber production} in forests~\cite{SRCCL2019}.
So it is no surprise that agricultural has important sustainability implications.

In addition to land use and GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}, agriculture has another 
major impact on sustainability: humans cannot live without food.
Agriculture does provide some nonfood products such as cotton, flax (for linen),
flowers, and leather.
However, this chapter will mostly focus on food products, in part because the 
sustainability characteristics that apply to food agriculture also apply to 
nonfood agriculture.
Food is the only source of energy humans can use to pursue lives of work, service, 
and play.
Moreover, food is the source of material inputs (``essential nutrients'') 
humans need to grow and maintain our bodies.
By definition, 
and in contrast to some of the examples mentioned in Section~\ref{sec:recycling},
``food'' is not a substitutable resource.
Although humans can exist on a wide variety of diets, we can't directly metabolize 
nonfood items, such as wood, cellulose\index{cellulose}, sunlight, or petroleum\index{petroleum}.

Food doesn't appear on plates magically, out of nowhere.
It arrives on our plates through a network of 
natural and human-created transformation processes\index{transformation processes!food}
that convert solar energy\index{solar energy}
into available, ingestible energy\index{ingestible energy}.
This network is often called ``agriculture.''
The combined economic value
of the agriculture, forestry, and fishing industries is 
about 1\% of GDP for the U.S.\ 
and about 3.5\% of GDP worldwide~\cite{World-Bank-agriculture:aa}.
However, the importance of agriculture goes far beyond its economic value.
Without agriculture, none of us would be here today!
This chapter presents key information about the food system and explores its 
sustainability challenges\index{sustainability challenges!agriculture}.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for agriculture}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Food consumption is rather predictable, because food requirements 
(measured in food calories, for example)
scale linearly with population. 
Over a long period of time, at least since 1870, 
when such things were first measured, 
the amount people eat, in pounds of food per day, 
has been relatively constant~\cite{Gordon2016}.
That's unsurprising, since
there is a fundamental, biological limit to the amount our bellies can hold.
However, in the U.S., there has been about a 22\% increase in calories consumed 
per person per day since 1967~\cite{Gordon2016}.
The trend has also been toward a more varied diet that includes more fresh foods.
This trend toward a richer, more varied diet repeats across the world as
affluence rises.
Thus, the global demand for food has two drivers:
population~\Pparen{} is the primary driver of demand for agriculture, and
affluence~\Aparen{} is a secondary driver.

As mentioned in Section~\ref{sec:PCbalance}, consumption and production are balanced,
particularly for food, in part because food spoils and humans prefer fresh food.
Sometimes, future food supply is cited as being a sustainability concern, usually on
the basis of past and current food production. 
However, because of the consumption/production balance, past and current production
is a poor indicator of future food production capacity.
Food is one of the few things humans can't do without.
Rising affluence (Figure~\ref{fig:AffluenceGraph-Nordhaus}) means there are lots
of things we could (and would) do without before we would give up food.
(The share of wealth\index{wealth} spent on food goes down as affluence rises, meaning food becomes
relatively cheaper as economies develop.
Indeed, the price of food has fallen, adjusted for inflation in the last 100 years.)
Furthermore, Section~\ref{sec:malthus_ehrlich_simon} indirectly suggests humanity 
will continue to have resources for food production, even if population grows substantially.
Therefore, total global food production should not be expected 
to be a major sustainability challenge\index{sustainability challenges!in food production}.
(Despite the fact that hunger remains an issue in the world today, 
food production is generally acknowledged to be adequate.
Instead, there are distribution problems due to factors such as poverty, 
government corruption\index{government corruption}, and
oppression.)

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} indicates reductions in agricultural impacts on the 
environment, in the absence of a falling population or affluence 
(Section~\ref{sec:reducing_c}), can only come from reducing 
one or both of the remaining terms,
the resource intensity of economic activity~\Rparen{} or the impact of resources~\Xparen{}.
The next section explores
sustainability challenges in agriculture\index{sustainability challenges!agriculture}, 
which arise from extracting resources 
from the ecosystem\index{ecosystem} faster than they regenerate and/or 
producing more waste\index{waste}(s) than the ecosystem\index{ecosystem} can absorb.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability challenges in agriculture}\index{sustainability challenges!agriculture}
\label{sec:ag_sust_challenges}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

When considering whether an activity is sustainable, 
resource depletion and environmental impacts are key questions.
That is, have the ecosystem's\index{ecosystem}
provisioning\index{provisioning services} and/or support services (Section~\ref{sec:ecosystem_services})
been exceeded?
For example, Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles} considered 
internal combustion engine (ICE) vehicles\index{internal combustion engine (ICE) vehicle}
and electric vehicles (EVs)\index{electric vehicle (EV)}.
A reliable sustainability comparison depends on an accurate accounting of inputs and outputs.
Section~\ref{sec:electric_vehicles} considered vehicle emissions
while in use, the energy and mineral resources\index{mineral resources} used to create each vehicle, and
the source of the power for each vehicle; 
see Figure~\ref{fig:auto_gwp}. 
% Each of these three accountings
% (direct emissions;
% vehicle emissions and the materials used to make the vehicle; or
% vehicle emissions, minerals\index{minerals} in the vehicle, 
% and power or fuel generation)
Each of way off accounting for inputs and outputs
gives a different nuance to the sustainability impacts
of vehicle manufacturing, use, and disposal.

In a similar manner,
defining appropriate inputs and outputs for agricultural sustainability 
is a key consideration.
Recall the definitions of weak\index{weak sustainability} and strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} from 
Section~\ref{sec:strong_weak_sust}.
Strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability} requires not using renewable resources 
faster than they can regenerate; 
see section~\ref{sec:what_is_sustainability}.
Consider \textbf{soil fertility}\index{soil fertility}, which is a renewable provisioning service\index{provisioning services} 
of the ecosystem\index{ecosystem}; 
see Chapter~\ref{chap:planetary_boundaries}.
If agricultural practices decrease soil fertility\index{soil fertility}, 
agriculture can not be considered strongly sustainable\index{strong sustainability}.
If agriculture depends on a nonrenewable resource, 
such as phosphate\index{phosphate} fertilizers\index{fertilizer},
it cannot be considered strongly sustainable\index{strong sustainability}.
If agriculture is rapidly depleting soil fertility\index{soil fertility}
such that the soil will be unusable in less than 50~years,
agriculture is not weakly sustainable\index{weak sustainability}.
The sections below examine the sustainability characteristics of several different
aspects of agriculture.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Soil and water} %% Agricultural use of landT
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Soil and water are the two most important inputs for agriculture.
As mentioned earlier, most of the usable land in the world 
is put to agricultural uses. 
Similarly, agriculture accounts for approximately 70\% of human freshwater use.
The paragraphs below examine a variety of unsustainable practices related to human 
use of land and water.


%..............................
\paragraph{Loss of soil fertility}\index{soil fertility} 
%..............................

Not all soils are rich in the nutrients needed by plants to grow.
\textbf{Topsoils}\index{topsoil} do contain the organic matter needed by plants.
However, topsoil\index{topsoil} can be lost by erosion due to the action of wind and/or water.
Most erosion results from wind or water action on tilled soils, that is,
where the land has been plowed to expose bare soil.
Some examples include the 1930s Dust Bowl\index{Dust Bowl} in the U.S.\
and the phenomenon called the ``Yellow Wind\index{Yellow Wind}'' or ``Asian dust\index{Asian dust},'' where fine
soil particles are carried from
China\index{China}, Mongolia\index{Mongolia}, and Kazakhstan\index{Kazakhstan} to East Asia\index{Asia} and 
sometimes across the Pacific Ocean\index{Pacific Ocean} to the U.S.
Some places in the Great Plains\index{Great Plains} have lost of several feet of topsoil\index{topsoil}.
For example, a survey in Minot, North Dakota\index{Minot, North Dakota} taken in 1900 found 40 cm of black
topsoil\index{topsoil}.
In 2017, the area had no black topsoil\index{topsoil}; its soil was light gray~\cite{Arnason:2017ug}.
Loss of topsoil\index{topsoil} reduces the productivity 
(in dollars of output per acre) of farmland\index{productivity!of farmland}.
Many arid and semi-arid regions are experiencing \textbf{desertification}\index{desertification} caused
by a combination of climate change\index{climate change} and poor agricultural practices.
The rate of erosion and runoff increases exponentially with the loss of vegetation 
cover~\cite{Geeson2003}. 
Unprotected soil surfaces are eroded by wind and water to leave unproductive 
inorganic subsoils that get baked by the sun\index{Sun} into a hardpan.
Soil fertility\index{soil fertility} can also be degraded by practices that withdraw key nutrients from the 
soil faster than they can be regenerated.
About 8\% of the total carbon in soils has been lost over the last 12,000
years~\cite{Sanderman2017}.

In contrast, 
sustainable agriculture\index{sustainable agriculture}
at least maintains, and hopefully builds, soil fertility\index{soil fertility}.
Soil fertility\index{soil fertility} and agricultural productivity\index{agricultural productivity}
can be enhanced with fertilizers\index{fertilizer} and/or agrichemicals\index{agrichemicals}.
The most common fertilizers\index{fertilizer} contain nitrogen\index{nitrogen (N)},
phosphorous\index{phosphorous (P)}, and potassium\index{potassium (K)}. 
Agrichemicals\index{agrichemicals} include herbicides\index{herbicide},
pesticides\index{pesticide}, and fungicides\index{fungicide}. 
To the extent that any of these are derived from nonrenewable feedstocks, such as 
fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, their use is not strongly sustainable\index{strong sustainability}.
Phosphate\index{phosphate (P)} fertilizers\index{fertilizer} are necessary for high 
\textbf{agricultural yields}\index{yield!agricultural}, but
they originate from (nonrenewable) mineral deposits.
On the other hand, about half of the fertilizer\index{fertilizer} used globally is manure\index{manure}, 
which is a renewable resource. 
Animal manure\index{manure} could be a sustainable fertilizer\index{fertilizer}, if the animals are raised sustainably,
for instance, and 
if their feed is sustainably raised.
A sustainability challenge associated with soil use\index{sustainability challenges!soil use} is 
``how can we maintain soil fertility\index{soil fertility}
in the long term without fertilizers\index{fertilizer} 
derived from nonrenewable resources?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\paragraph{Water---quantity and quality}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Plants need water to grow.
Currently, much of agricultural irrigation\index{irrigation} is not sustainable because water is being
extracted from aquifers\index{aquifer} faster than the natural regeneration rate.
If aquifers\index{aquifer} are exhausted, future humans won't have water for nourishment or bathing.
Overuse of water is not limited to subsurface water, like the Ogallala aquifer\index{Ogallala aquifer}; 
see \ref{question:ogallala}. 
Surface water is also being overused for agriculture.
One particularly notable example is the (former) Aral Sea\index{Aral Sea}, which has all but disappeared
due to diversion of its water for irrigation\index{irrigation}; see Figure~\ref{fig:aral_sea}.
Another example is the Colorado River\index{Colorado River}, which 
supplies water to 12\% of the U.S.\ population
and 
supports 15\% of U.S.\ crop output and
  13\% of U.S.\ livestock production~\cite{UWMCWP2014}. 
%% https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lYvQNon4aLg&t=804s
%% https://feedingourselvesthirsty.ceres.org/regional-analysis/colorado-river
%% https://uwm.edu/centerforwaterpolicy/wp-content/uploads/sites/170/2013/10/Colorado_Agriculture_Final.pdf
Because of diversions for agriculture (70--80\%) and 
supplying municipalities with drinking water (15\%),
the Colorado River\index{Colorado River} mouth is dry; 
it no longer flows into the Sea of Cortez\index{Sea of Cortez}.


