Agricultural activities also result in water pollution\index{pollution!water} of surface water and ground water.
For example, the city of Toledo, Ohio\index{Toledo, Ohio} draws its drinking water from Lake Erie\index{Lake Erie}.
Since the 1990s, Lake Erie\index{Lake Erie} has been subject to ``blooms'' of toxic cyanobacteria\index{cyanobacteria}
fueled by fertilizer\index{fertilizer} run off.
Six people got sick in 2013.
In 2014, 110 people got sick and the municipal water supply to 400,000 people was shut down.
Moreover, Lake Erie\index{Lake Erie} and the Maumee River\index{Maumee River} that feeds it were unsafe for human skin contact.
Blooms occurred again in 2017 and 2019~\cite{Rogener:2020wi}.
Animal manure\index{manure} can also contaminate waterways. Ick.

A sustainability challenge associated with agricultural use
of water\index{sustainability challenges!water} is 
“how can we maintain sufficient sources of clean water for agriculture and
(direct) human use?''


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Energy}
\label{sec:food_energy_return_ratios}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
 
The energy input to agriculture ranges from human and animal 
labor\index{labor} to electricity and hydrocarbon fuels, either fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}
or biofuels\index{biofuel}.
Energy is used at all stages of agriculture, from preparing the ground to sow crops,
to harvesting, storage, transportation, cooking, and disposal of food.
Because food is humanity's energy source\index{energy source}, we should consider its
energy return on investment\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}
(EROI, defined in Section~\ref{sec:masterE}).
When EROI~>~1, food is an energy source for humans, that is,
we obtain more energy from the food than it took to obtain the food.
When EROI~<~1, we spend more energy obtaining the food than we get 
from the food. 
Since we must have food, it is worth spending energy on.


