Because food is energy, the overall energy return on investment (EROI)\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} 
and efficiency of the food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system} can be calculated.
Figure~\ref{fig:food_and_ag_energy_flow} shows the energy consumed and supplied
by various aspects of the food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system} in the U.S.
The EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} of food produced is 
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_gross * 100, fmt = "%#.1f")}\%
(\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_gross_output, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads of food energy
produced per
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_denominator, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads of energy input).
In other words, it takes
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_scaled_input, fmt = "%#.2f")} calories of energy input
to produce one calorie of food energy.
However, because of waste, the situation is actually much worse.
A significant fraction
(\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_waste_fraction * 100, fmt = "%#.1f")}\%)
of food that is produced is wasted\index{food waste}
(\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_waste, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads wasted\index{waste!energy} out of
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_gross_output, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads produced).
Taking waste\index{waste} into account, the EROI of food consumed is
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi * 100, fmt = "%#.1f")}\%
(\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_consumed, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads consumed, 
\Sexpr{sprintf(food_eroi_denominator, fmt = "%#.2f")} quads input).
The fact that the EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}
of the food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system} is less than 100\%
means that the food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system} is not a source of energy for society.
Rather, it is a sink of energy for society.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Animals that spend more energy to obtain food than they gain from eating food 
ultimately die from lack of energy.
Agrarian societies that spend more energy to obtain food 
than they gain from eating food ultimately cease to exist.
Without fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, the modern food system would collapse
and modern society with it.
\end{mcframe}

To put it another way, human society today spends more energy
to obtain food than it gets from food.  
Whether spending more energy to obtain food than we get from it is sustainable or not
depends on where the energy for agriculture comes from. 
Modern society remains viable only
because its food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system} is supported by energy inputs from an external source:
fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}. 
Fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}
supply the energy for 
machines in agriculture, food transportation, food processing, food packaging, 
retail, food storage, and food preparation.
Because (a)~agricultural EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} is less than 1 
and
(b)~energy for agriculture comes from fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}, 
today's agricultural system is not sustainable.

One view of the agricultural system is as a huge machine 
with the purpose of converting feed for animals into food for humans.
Both feed and food can be quantified in energy terms (in units of kcal).
Thus, in that view, the entire agricultural system can be characterized by an efficiency, 
the ratio of kcal of food output to kcal of feed input.
The \textbf{feed-to-food efficiency~($\eta_{\mft{ff}}$)}\index{feed-to-food efficiency ($\eta_{\mft{ff}}$)}
quantifies the efficiency of these agricultural processes.
The overall feed-to-food efficiency\index{feed-to-food efficiency ($\eta_{\mft{ff}}$)} of the U.S.\ food system 
is about 7\%~\cite{Shepon:2016wt}.
Different types of food have different feed-to-food efficiencies\index{feed-to-food efficiency ($\eta_{\mft{ff}}$)},
as shown in Figure~\ref{fig:FoodToFeedEfficiency}.

