\paragraph{CO$_2$}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

One source of GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!food} in food and agriculture 
is the food-delivery system\index{food-delivery system}.
Figure~\ref{fig:food_ghg} shows GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!food} from the various stages of food
distribution and preparation. 
The amount of CO$_2$ released is proportional to the amount of energy used.
Figure~\ref{fig:FoodEmissionsPerMcal} shows equivalent CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!food} per Mcal of food.
(Foods with low feed-to-food efficiency\index{feed-to-food efficiency ($\eta_{\mft{ff}}$)}
tend to have higher GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!food};
see Figure~\ref{fig:FoodToFeedEfficiency}.)
However, by itself Figure~\ref{fig:FoodEmissionsPerMcal} is not terribly informative.
We don't eat equal calories of each food.
We need a balanced diet that provides all of our essential
nutrients.
Figure~\ref{fig:GHG_food} shows what individual foods contribute to overall food
emissions (but not what quantity of each are consumed).
Taken together, Figures~\ref{fig:food_ghg}--\ref{fig:GHG_food} 
illustrate agricultural CO$_2$ emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions!agriculture}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\paragraph{CH$_4$}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

One tonne of methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)}
has the same global warming potential\index{global warming potential (GWP)} as twenty five tonnes 
of CO$_2$---methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} is a very potent GHG.
Methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} is about 10\% of U.S.\ GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}. 
Of this 10\%, about 39\% comes from agriculture, 40\% comes from energy and transportation,
and 21\% comes from landfills and wastewater treatment~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.
Agricultural emissions are almost entirely from enteric digestion and manure\index{manure} management,
with a small amount (6\%) coming from rice cultivation.
Enteric digestion refers to the production of methane in an animal's digestion.
The amount of methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} produced depends on the quality of the animal's feed.
Seventy-two percent of methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} from enteric digestion comes from beef cattle\index{cattle!beef};
24\% is from dairy cattle\index{cattle!dairy}~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.
Methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} from manure management tends to come from liquified manure\index{manure} treatment, which
is often the preferred method for concentrated animal populations.
Dairy cattle\index{cattle!dairy} account for 51.3\% of methane\index{methane (CH$_4$)} from manure\index{manure}
and swine\index{pig} account for 37\%~\cite{USEPA:2021uj}.

A sustainability challenge associated agricultural
GHG emissions\index{sustainability challenges!GHG emissions}
is ``how can we eliminate GHG emissions from agriculture?''


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability transitions in agriculture}
\label{sec:food_ag_efficiency}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This section describes changes needed to make agriculture more sustainable.
% The focus of this section is on what changes are needed for sustainability. 
% (Chapters~\ref{chap:government} and~\ref{chap:personal_action} are complementary
% to this section, in that they focus on who makes changes for sustainability
% and how those changes will be made.)
One obvious category of change appears from viewing agriculture through the lens
of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX}.
To have reduced impacts \Iparen{}, agriculture needs to 
use fewer inputs to deliver the food society needs: 
less land, less water, less energy, and less fertilizer\index{fertilizer} and agrichemicals\index{agrichemicals}.
These changes would reduce the resource intensity
\Rparen{} of agriculture.
Another, related, set of changes would be to lower 
the impact of resources consumed by agriculture~\Xparen{}, 
for example, less runoff, less desertification\index{desertification}, less groundwater contamination.
We leave to Chapters~\ref{chap:government} and~\ref{chap:personal_action} the 
discussion of how such changes can be made (when possible) and who might take action
to make such changes.

Any measure that will increase the efficiency or efficacy of the food system\index{food system efficacy} is 
a step towards becoming more sustainable.
For example, reducing food waste\index{food waste} has multiple effects:
eliminating the inputs needed to grow wasted food,
reducing the emissions from producing, consuming, and disposing of that food), and
increasing the effective EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)} of the food system.

It is worth noting that enhanced agricultural productivity\index{agricultural productivity}, 
efficacy\index{agricultural efficacy}, or efficiency 
(depending on the metric under consideration) 
may be subject to limited rebound\index{rebound effect}
(Section~\ref{sec:rebound_effect})
in the agriculture sector itself,
a difference from rebound effects\index{rebound effect} from energy efficiency\index{energy efficiency}.
One aspect of the rebound effect\index{rebound effect} involves using more of the energy service\index{energy service} 
when it becomes cheaper. 
For instance, when an automobile\index{automobile} has a lower energy intensity (fewer gallons per mile),
driving becomes cheaper, so more miles are driven.
However, in agriculture, the ``appetite'' for food is essentially fixed. 
Cheaper food should not result in greatly increased demand for food.
Certainly, savings from agriculture will be spent in other areas of the economy
(another important aspect of rebound\index{rebound effect}),
but we don't expect to see a strong rebound\index{rebound effect} within the agriculture sector itself.
(The magnitude of rebound\index{rebound effect}
outside the sector in which efficiency improves
is a matter of debate.)

Another positive change for the sustainability of agriculture would be to transition
the world's energy supply to renewable energy\index{renewable energy}, 
given the energy-intensive nature of modern agriculture and 
its attendant low EROI\index{energy return on investment (EROI)}.
Of course, a transition to renewable energy\index{renewable energy} would benefit more sectors than just agriculture;
it would be universally beneficial and, in fact, is necessary 
for strong sustainability\index{strong sustainability}.

Renewable energy\index{renewable energy} sources require lots of land (Figure~\ref{fig:PowerDensity}), 
land that is already mostly used for agriculture.
One strategy could be to combine agriculture and renewable energy\index{renewable energy} generation
on the same land. 
For instance, animals can graze among the turbines\index{wind turbine} of a wind farm\index{wind farm}.
Another option could be to use solar panels\index{solar panel} to provide partial shade for crops that 
prefer partial shade, like coffee\index{coffee} or raspberries\index{raspberry}. 
The plants provide some cooling for the solar panels\index{solar panel}, thereby boosting the
energy generation efficiency of the panels.
The panels provide shade for crops, thereby reducing the amount of water needed 
for irrigation\index{irrigation}.
The tradeoff is that panel spacing may be less dense than would be typical for 
industrial photovoltaic\index{solar photovoltaic electricity} installation, so the crops have to make up the difference in 
profitability per acre.

Since the transition to renewable energy\index{renewable energy} is the topic of 
Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition}, we won't revisit it here. 
Instead, the rest of this section focuses on two further transitions necessary
for agricultural sustainability: shifts in agricultural
practices to be resilient\index{resilience} to the effects of climate change\index{climate change} and the need for 
regenerative agriculture\index{regenerative agriculture}.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Climate change resiliency}
\label{sec:ag_CC_resilience}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

%Water. Heat. Changing weather patterns. Growing zones will change. Pests and invasive species.
Climate change\index{climate change} is already presenting challenges for agriculture\index{sustainability challenges!agriculture}. 
Ensuring that humanity has enough food in the future requires that agriculture change 
to become resilient\index{resilience} to the effects of climate change\index{climate change}. 
The need for climate-change resilience\index{resilience} is present in many areas of society and the
economy, not just agriculture.
However, given the almost unique position of agriculture on the land, in the weather,
and in the natural world, agriculture is the perfect example for discussing the need for
climate-change resiliency\index{resilience}.

Warmer average global temperatures increase plants' need for water; they cool themselves
by \textbf{transpiration}\index{transpiration}.
However, water supplies are threatened by climate change\index{climate change}: surface water (rivers, lakes, and
reservoirs) evaporates more rapidly in warmer air.
Moreover, climate change\index{climate change} is altering weather and climate patterns, such as distribution
of precipitation.
Extreme weather events are generally becoming more frequent and more destructive.
Natural pests and/or invasive species may expand their range or period of activity
due to a changing climate.

Another effect of climate change\index{climate change} is a shifting of growing regions, generally towards
higher latitudes. 
Some crops may be forced away from their traditional growing regions by hotter, 
drier climates.
Hotter, drier climates also bring the increased risk of desertification\index{desertification}.

On the one hand, there may be a temptation to ``double down'' on all the agricultural
practices that have fed us through the population boom of the last century, namely,
the use of large amounts of inputs, such as fossil energy\index{fossil fuels},
synthetic fertilizers\index{fertilizer}, and agrichemicals\index{agrichemicals}
to maximize agricultural productivity\index{agricultural productivity}.
On the other hand, increasing inputs will accelerate soil depletion, intensity runoff
and other agricultural emissions, and shorten the weak sustainability\index{weak sustainability} horizon for the 
use of nonrenewable resources such as petroleum\index{petroleum}, fossil water\index{fossil water}, and
phosphate\index{phosphate (P)} deposits.
The climate-change crisis provides an opportunity to rethink ``business as usual\index{business as usual}'' and to 
develop new practices that will be effective on a warmer planet.


%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Agriculture to sequester carbon}
\label{sec:ag_C_sequest}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

As mentioned above, agriculture and land use are a significant source of humanity's 
GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}. 
For sustainability, agriculture must become a carbon sink rather than a source 
for carbon emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}. 
Human agricultural practices over the last 12,000 years (but mostly since 1800) 
have released 116~Gt of carbon from the Earth's soil~\cite[Fig.~2]{Sanderman2017}.
Returning carbon to the soil would make the soil more fertile and would have
positive climate-change implications.
Figure~\ref{fig:Fig-SPM-10} indicates we have roughly 3000~Gt of CO$_2$ to remove
from the atmosphere\index{atmosphere}. 
Replacing 116~Gt of carbon in the soil would remove 425.3~Gt of CO$_2$ from the
atmosphere\index{atmosphere}.
In other words, sequestering carbon in the soil would be a significant step toward
solving the current climate crisis.

\textbf{Regenerative agriculture}\index{Regenerative agriculture}
is a set of land management practices that builds 
soil health by, among other things, sequestering carbon in the soil. 
Which regenerative agriculture\index{regenerative agriculture} techniques are most effective varies with site history, 
location, and biome, but 
it is common to use managed grazing by livestock 
as a key component of soil enhancement.
Thus, while beef\index{cattle!beef} and dairy cattle\index{cattle!dairy} are
sources of GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions} under most current 
agricultural practices, in regenerative agriculture\index{regenerative agriculture} they can play a role in net
carbon sequestration\index{carbon sequestration}~\cite{WOP2019}.
See~\ref{project:regenerative_ag} for some tips on investigating
regenerative agriculture\index{regenerative agriculture} in more detail.


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Summary}
\label{sec:food_transitions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Agriculture exists to feed the world's population~\Pparen.
To be more sustainability, 
agriculture must use as few resources as possible and cause minimal 
impact on the environment. 
Currently, agricultural uses unsustainable mineral inputs and
involves land-use practices that degrade soil fertility\index{soil fertility} and harm the land's ability to 
sequester carbon.
In today's economy, agriculture is an energy sink\index{energy sink} rather than an energy source\index{energy source}, 
requiring the unsustainable input of fossil fuels\index{fossil fuels}.
Agriculture is inefficient on both mass and energy bases.
Unfortunately, today's agriculture system causes significant GHG emissions\index{CO$_2$ emissions}.
Reducing environmental impacts from agriculture will require additional investment, which
may make food more expensive.
However, food is a basic human need; 
it is one of the few things we absolutely cannot do without.
Therefore, it is crucially important to make choices, individually and corporately,
that make the agriculture system more sustainable, 
while resolving distributional issues and improving food access for all.

A seven-word ``recipe'' for sustainable agriculture\index{sustainable agriculture} is
given by food writer Michael Pollan\index{Pollan, Michael}:
``[e]at food. Not too much. Mostly plants.''


